pip install PyPDF2

Requirement already satisfied: PyPDF2 in /usr/local/lib/python3.10/dist-packages (3.0.1)

Ingestion Service¶

1. Design the approach and extract text data from input pdf file. Explain the step by step process of data parsing mechanism for text extraction¶

Detailed Parsing mechanism:¶

  1. Define Requirements:Type: Text extracted from PDF file. Format: PDF format, which contains text, images, tables, etc..
  2. Parsing the identified data format like PyMuPDF or PyPDF2 for PDF parsing. In this case , PyPDF2 is used
  3. Extract text from page: Extract text from each page. Clean and organize extracted text.Validate the data by printing and verifying.
  4. Extract content from Unstructured Data: There are many libraries to extract unstructured data from this document. In this project tesseract library is used to extract the information.Validate the output against expected results.
  5. Chunking: Every text is grouped across chunk_size=300 and overlap of 50 tokens.
  6. Vectorization: Generate text embedding for all the text chunks. To vectorize the chunks, sentence transformer is used, here using MiniLM model.
  7. Store data to vector store: FAISS - Index is used. Once vectorization is completed, these vectors will be stored in database like Vector DB or Croma DB. We used FAISS.

#Step 1: Load the PDF File
import PyPDF2

Renamed the file as 'sop_con'¶

# Load PDF file
pdf_file_name = '/sop_con.pdf'
In [ ]:
pdf_reader = PyPDF2.PdfReader(txtpath+pdf_file_name)
In [ ]:
#Step 2: Extract Text from Each Page
text_data = []
for page_num in range(len(pdf_reader.pages)):
    page = pdf_reader.pages[page_num]
    text = page.extract_text()
    text_data.append(text)
In [ ]:
#Step 3: Clean and Organize Extracted Text
import re

def clean_text(text):
    # Remove multiple spaces, newlines, and tabs
    text = re.sub(r'\s+', ' ', text)
    return text

cleaned_text_data = [clean_text(text) for text in text_data]

for line in cleaned_text_data[:5]:
    print(line)

SOP for Supply Chain Management under NACP1 India is committed to ‘Ending the AIDS’ epidemic as a public health threat by 2030 in line with Sustainable Development Goals (SDG). As we move forward, we will continue to ensure that all people living with HIV, and those at risk, receive a comprehensive package of life-saving services for HIV prevention, testing, treatment and care. Across NACO & SACS, Supply Chain Management (SCM) of HIV/ AIDS commodities involves a series of activities to ensure a continuous supply of products from the point of manufacture to the point of care. The supply chain function provides programme managers with data to help define the products required. The data helps them operate efficiently within the system and plan the availability of the products with efficient deliveries in relation to quality, quantity and time. In terms of supply chain management, a greater integration within the health care system is proposed in the way ahead. Procurement and supply chain management is one of the critical enablers in National AIDS Control Programme (NACP) also and central to ensuring continuous, uninterrupted supply of commodities. The lack of a well-functioning SCM is a threat to the implementation of prevention programme, delivery of HIV testing services, and treatment, care and support for HIV.This document shall guide our joint efforts in the next coming years to fast-track organisation’s capacity to better manage HIV/AIDS supply chain in India. The implementation of these SOPs will be a comprehensive elevation of procurement and supply chain function and needs to be used as a reference at every level to accelerate efforts to end AIDS and help us realise our planned outcomes. The National AIDS Control Organization remains committed to assist all stakeholders with the implementation of this SOP to garner optimal outcomes in each specific setting.I hope the SOPs for HIV/ AIDS Supply Chain Management will be helpful to all those who are involved in the field of policy, administration, planning, management & research of health services and ensure timely service provision to clients.Dated the 30th September, 2020 Message

Convert PDF pages to images, specifying extraction from the filepath in the form of bytes¶

In [ ]:
# Set the path to Tesseract executable if needed
#pytesseract.pytesseract.tesseract_cmd = r'C:\Program Files\Tesseract-OCR\tesseract.exe'  # Adjust the path as per your installation

def extract_text_from_pdf(file_path):

    images = convert_from_bytes(open(file_path,'rb').read(),size=500)

    extracted_text = []
    for image in images:
        # Use pytesseract to do OCR on each image
        text = pytesseract.image_to_string(image)
        extracted_text.append(text)

    return extracted_text

# Function to clean the extracted text
def clean_text(text):
    text = re.sub(r'\s+', ' ', text)
    return text

Convert text into chunks and explain the logic of chunking strategy¶

Chunking Strategy: OCR Extracted Text is saved in structured JSON format.¶

  • Every text is grouped across chunk_size = 300 and an overlap of 50 tokens - Word split (tokens) is considered.
  • The data has unnecessary spaces, literals, required a cleaning structure, appended the chunks with overlap chunks post cleaned.
  • we are persisting the json data that is chunked.
In [ ]:
import json

# Load the extracted text data from the JSON file
with open(txtpath+'/ocr_extracted_text.json', 'r') as f:
    cleaned_text_data = json.load(f)
In [ ]:
# Define the chunking logic
def chunk_text(text, chunk_size=300, overlap=50):
    words = text.split()
    chunks = []
    start = 0
    while start < len(words):
        end = start + chunk_size
        chunk = words[start:end]
        chunks.append(' '.join(chunk))
        start += chunk_size - overlap
    return chunks
In [ ]:
# Apply the chunking logic to the extracted text
all_chunks = []
for text in cleaned_text_data:
    chunks = chunk_text(text, chunk_size=500, overlap=50)
    all_chunks.extend(chunks)

Strategy and Embedding model Implementation:¶

  • Used Sentence Transformer pretrained model - 'all-MiniLM-L6-v2' with 384 dimensions
  • Generated text embeddings for all text chunks.
  • It uses the "sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2" model to create vector representations of text.
  • This model is known for its efficiency in creating semantic embeddings.
In [ ]:
# Load the pretrained model
model = SentenceTransformer('all-MiniLM-L6-v2') # 384 dimensions

# Generate embeddings for all text chunks
embeddings = model.encode(text_chunks, convert_to_tensor=True)

Ingest data to the vector store. Use vector DB like croma DB or any other open source vector DB as a knowledge base¶

We use FAISS as vector DB, current section contains:¶

  • VectorDB imports
    • This section imports various components from llama_index for document processing, indexing, and querying.
    • It sets up FAISS (Facebook AI Similarity Search) for efficient similarity search in high-dimensional spaces.
In [ ]:
import faiss
from llama_index.embeddings.huggingface import HuggingFaceEmbedding
In [ ]:
from IPython.display import Markdown, display
from llama_index.core import VectorStoreIndex,SimpleDirectoryReader,ServiceContext,load_index_from_storage,StorageContext
from llama_index.llms.huggingface import HuggingFaceLLM #interact with hub
from llama_index.core.prompts.prompts import SimpleInputPrompt
In [ ]:
from llama_index.vector_stores.faiss import FaissVectorStore
In [ ]:
dimensions = 384
faiss_index = faiss.IndexFlatL2(dimensions)

documents = SimpleDirectoryReader(txtpath+'/pdfs').load_data()

Ingest into Vector Store and Index Creation¶

  • This section sets up the vector store and creates the index:
  • It initializes a FAISS index with the embedding dimension of 384 (the same as the embedding model)
  • It creates a vector store using this index.
  • It then builds a VectorStoreIndex from the documents, using the embedding model.
  • The index is persisted for future use.
In [ ]:
vector_store = FaissVectorStore(faiss_index=faiss_index)
In [ ]:
# Load embedding model
embed_model = HuggingFaceEmbedding(model_name="sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2")
storage_context = StorageContext.from_defaults(vector_store=vector_store)

Retrieval Service¶

1. Design the retrieval pipeline of the framework that will be leveraged for the end to end pipeline .¶

Designing the Retrieval Pipeline: Theory

  1. Data Ingestion Objective: • To read and load PDF files into the system for processing. Details: • The first step in the retrieval pipeline is to acquire the PDF files from their source. This is done from a local directory in colab. • Tools and Libraries: PyPDF2 for opening and reading PDF files.
  2. Data Parsing Objective: • To extract raw text data from the loaded PDF files. Details: • Once the PDF file is loaded, the next step is to parse the file and extract text data. This involves reading each page of the PDF and extracting the textual content. • Tools and Libraries: Leverage any open source OCR extraction library to extract the content from unstructured document. We are using tesseract library
  3. Data Preprocessing Objective: • To clean and preprocess the extracted text data for further analysis. Details: • The raw text extracted from PDF files often contains noise such as special characters, extra spaces, and stop words that are not useful for analysis. Preprocessing involves steps like tokenization, converting text to lowercase, removing punctuation and stop words, and stemming or lemmatization. This step ensures that the data is in a structured format suitable for analysis or further processing.
  4. Data – Chunks Vector Embeddings Objective: • To store the processed data in a structured format for easy retrieval and analysis. Details: • Data is broken down into chunks and embedding vectors are created which is stored in vector database • Tools and Libraries: Used Sentence Transformer pretrained model - 'all-MiniLM-L6-v2' with 384 dimensions. It uses the "sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2" model to create vector representations of text
  5. Vector Store – Indexing Tools: FAISS is used as Vector store and embeddings are indexed and mapped into open source DB. Also, LLAMAINDEX is used to index.Storage Index mechanism is used to for fetching documents with the embeddings.
  6. RAG Querying - Retrieval Service Details: • Leverage open source LLM to generate user query for information retrieval with LLAMA-2 context window of size 4096. Loaded in 8 bit quantised format. • We set up top similarity to 5 to have more exhaustive answers against the LLAMA-2 llm model.

Sample diagram that explains our strategy [websource]¶

Leverage open source LLM to generate user query for information retrieval¶

Leveraging LLama-2 and writing query wrapper, system prompts around the llm¶

In [ ]:
import torch

Language Model Setup and Loading:¶

  • It uses the "llama-2-7b-chat" model, a powerful instruction-tuned language model.
  • It configures 8-bit quantization to reduce memory usage
  • The model is configured with specific generation parameters and quantization for efficiency.
In [ ]:
llm_model = HuggingFaceLLM(
    context_window = 4096,
    # max_new_token = 256,
    generate_kwargs= {"temperature":0.0,"do_sample": False},
    system_prompt = system_prompt,
    query_wrapper_prompt=query_wrapper_prompt,
    tokenizer_name = "meta-llama/Llama-2-7b-chat-hf",
    model_name = "meta-llama/Llama-2-7b-chat-hf",
    device_map = "auto",
    model_kwargs= {"torch_dtype": torch.float16, "load_in_8bit": True
                   }
    )

The `load_in_4bit` and `load_in_8bit` arguments are deprecated and will be removed in the future versions. Please, pass a `BitsAndBytesConfig` object in `quantization_config` argument instead.

RAG Querying - Retrieval Service¶

  • We expect more accurate and truthful answers.

query_engine = index.as_query_engine(llm=llm_model, similarity_top_k=5)

Observations from direct RAG querying¶

  • There is a array of responses for every query, however System failed to retrieve effective ones for Query_1 : "list the scope of Receive and Store Commodities in less than 50 words"[to give restricted token length]
  • Response is exhaustive
  • Similarly for Query_3 ""What is HIV Test Kits flow process""
  • For query_2 ""what is AIDS distribution among gender?" , system cohesively grouped relevant top 5 docs and presented near accurate response

Enhancement : Customizing the stages of querying through LLAMAINDEX Response Synthesizer¶

  • We customize our retriever to use a different number for top_k and add a post-processing step that requires that the retrieved nodes reach a minimum similarity score to be included. Here it is. 0.7
  • This would give you more richer, relevant results but potentially no data if you have nothing relevant.
In [ ]:
from llama_index.core import VectorStoreIndex, get_response_synthesizer
from llama_index.core.retrievers import VectorIndexRetriever
from llama_index.core.query_engine import RetrieverQueryEngine
from llama_index.core.postprocessor import SimilarityPostprocessor


# configure retriever
retriever = VectorIndexRetriever(
    index=index,
    similarity_top_k=10,
)

# configure response synthesizer
response_synthesizer = get_response_synthesizer(llm=llm_model)

# assemble query engine
query_engine = RetrieverQueryEngine(
    retriever=retriever,
    response_synthesizer=response_synthesizer,
    node_postprocessors=[SimilarityPostprocessor(similarity_cutoff=0.7)],
)
In [ ]:
# query
response = query_engine.query("What is HIV Test Kits flow process")
print(response)

Observation:¶

  • The Query_1 and Query_3 which were exhaustive and irrelevant , now caters to significant improvement with similarity thresholds.
  • Further the strategy can be refined by tuning chunk size, effective retriever in place.

Add required guardrails to improve the retrieval mechanism.¶

Challenges and Guard rails:

  1. Data Quality and Diversity: Depends on the Quality of Source Document,PDF data encoding format, styles, image layouts and efficient extraction is subjectively dependent on the framework used.
  2. Chunk Text and Contextual Limitations: For the ease of execution, Used chunksize of 300,with overlap of 50. However, this depends on the data validation and extraction of chunk embeddings. Based on it, we can leverage this parameter.
  3. Pretrained LLM -Model; The usage of LLAMA_2 comes with its own trained challenges and quantization of 16 to 8 bits is leveraged to make sure the model drives in colab.
  4. Relevance and Comprehensiveness: To maintain relvancy of responses, we customized the stages of querying through LLAMAINDEX Response Synthesizer.
  5. Basic Retriever is used:Similarity search algorithm between the query and the documents in the vector store. We can look for BM25 or fusion retriever if needed for better relevancy.
